    "created_at": "2016-03-08T23:35:48Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-03-08T23:36:12Z",
    "body": "After thinking about this a bit and looking at the Mac OS X docs, I think we should add a new option to `BrowserWindow`:\n- `titleBarHeight: <pixels from top of window>`\n\nThis would be the vertical offset at which sheets should be positioned. I'd also like to change the behavior of `titleBarStyle` (an existing option) on Mac OS X. The current behavior is:\n- `titleBarStyle`: `hidden` results in a hidden title bar and a full size content window, yet the title bar still has the standard window controls (\"traffic lights\") in the top left.\n- `titleBarStyle`: `hidden-inset` results in a hidden title bar with an alternative look where the traffic light buttons are slightly more inset from the window edge.\n\nThe problem is that \"slightly more inset\" is not quite right for our app which uses a Safari-sized toolbar that is 38px tall. (They're too far down) I think we should deprecate the `hidden-inset` option and instead make `hidden` automatically position the window controls so they are centered within the `titleBarHeight` if it's provided. So for example, `titleBarStyle:hidden, titleBarHeight: 80` would center the buttons 40px from the top of the window and display sheets 80px from the top of the window.\n\n@zcbenz does that sound good? I can submit a patch for this if that approach makes sense.\n"
  },
